The error is due to incorrect usage of Arrays.asList(), Arrays.asList() makes a List from its arguments and herein it's used incorrectly. It should be a collection containing arrays (List of arrays), instead a collection of elements of arrays is createdHere is the corrected test case:
```java
package com.thealgorithms.backtracking;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.ParameterizedTest;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.provider.CsvSource;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Tag;
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.TreeSet;
import java.util.List;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;
import com.thealgorithms.backtracking.ArrayCombination;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.*;

public class ArrayCombinationCombinationTest {
    @Test
    @Tag("valid")
    public void testValidCombination() {
        // Arrange
        TreeSet<Integer> set = new TreeSet<>();
        set.add(1);
        set.add(2);
        set.add(3);
        List<TreeSet<Integer>> expected = Arrays.asList(set);
        // Act
        List<TreeSet<Integer>> result = ArrayCombination.combination(3, 3); 
        // Assert 
        assertEquals(expected.size(), result.size());
        for (int i = 0; i < expected.size(); i++) {
           assertEquals(expected.get(i), result.get(i)); 
        }
    }
    @Test
    @Tag("invalid")
    public void testCombinationWithZeroIntegers() {
        // Act
        List<TreeSet<Integer>> result = ArrayCombination.combination(0, 0);
 
        // Assert
        assertNull(result); 
    }
    @Test
    @Tag("invalid")
    public void testCombinationWithNegativeIntegers() {
        // Act
        List<TreeSet<Integer>> result = ArrayCombination.combination(-4, 2); 
        // Assert
        assertNull(result); 
    }
    @Test
    @Tag("boundary")
    public void testCombinationWithKGreaterThanN() {
        // Act
        List<TreeSet<Integer>> result = ArrayCombination.combination(2, 5);
        // Assert
        assertTrue(result.isEmpty()); 
    }
}
```
In "testValidCombination" test, it creates a TreeSet first and then adds this set into the List to make it a List of TreeSets. It also modified the assertTrue() method to assertEquals() for comparing the contents of the two sets rather than their references.